<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1620 GMT, September 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG -- Negotiators of the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK) and South Korea have reached agreement on seven
issues after three days of ministerial-level talks, a joint
statement said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have agreed to hold military talks to ease
tension on the peninsula. They also agreed on two more family
reunions this year, the establishment of a regime to protect
investment and avoid double taxation, the restoration of a railway
between South Korean capital Seoul and Sin'uiju in the north. (
DPRK-SKorea-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesian President Abdurrahman Wahid Friday
indicated that the trial process against former president Soeharto
should go on despite the absence of the defendant in the first
hearing on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Wahid made the statement in response some parties which were
worried that Thursday's absence of the former strongman from the
court would hamper the long-waited trial process. (Soeharto-trial)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak Friday admitted
that he did not know at this time whether he and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat could break the deadlock on the fate of
Jerusalem for reaching a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
Since the Camp David summit between Barak, Arafat and U.S.
President Bill Clinton collapsed last month, it became more and
more clear that the thorniest issue between the two sides is the
status of Jerusalem. (Israel-Palestinians-Jerusalem)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- The chief French investigator for the crash of Air
France Concorde said Friday that no final report explaining the
cause of the crash will be published in months or even years.
</P>
<P>
Paul-Louis Arslanian, director of the Bureau of Accident
Investigation (BEA), told the press that the bureau is still
analyzing the problem about the tire on the undercarriage of the
Concorde which apparently burst when it was taking off. (France-
Concorde)
</P>
<P>
- - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on Friday delayed the
decision-making on the deployment of a national missile defense (
NMD) system to his successor.  (US-NMD-Delay) 
</P>
