<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South African Govt. Urged to Speed up Pace of Black Empowerment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government has to give more attention to deracializing economy,
especially by accelerating the pace of black empowerment and
affirmative action, Education Minister Kader Asmal said here on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We need to deliberately and consciously work on genuine
programs of empowerment and the transference of resources and
skills to larger parts of the black community rather than to a few
hand-picked individuals," said Asmal, member of a panel addressing
delegates at the on-going national conference on racism held in
Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
"We need programs that will make a visible and lasting impact
on the lives of black people," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Professor Linda Human, another panel member who is a consultant
in workplace transformation, said any strategies to remove
discrimination from places of employment had to be driven by top
management, who had to ensure affirmative action targets were
reached.
</P>
<P>
Companies had to be held accountable to make sure their
organizational culture was free of racism, Human said, adding that
codes of conduct had to be established to regulate workplace
behavior. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
