<HEADLINE> Liberian President Urges Guinea to Expel Liberian Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Liberian President Charles
Taylor has urged his Guinean counterpart Lansana Conte to expel
Liberian rebels allegedly based in his country, according to
reports reaching here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"I do not have a problem with Lansana Conte personally. We can
engage Guinea in dialogue to put a halt to the bust-up. This
government does not have a problem with Guinea," Taylor was quoted
as saying on Thursday on the state radio.
</P>
<P>
Liberian government forces have been battling rebels in the
north of the country since the rebels who allegedly entered from
Guinea about two month ago. Most of the fighting has taken place
in the Voinjama area, provincial capital of Lofa County bordering
Guinea.
</P>
<P>
"There is a need for the Guinean government to take the war in
Lofa seriously so that its territory should not be used," the
president said.
</P>
<P>
Taylor has accused Guinea of harboring the dissidents bent on
toppling his administration, a charge Guinea repeatedly rejects.
</P>
</TEXT>
