<HEADLINE> S. Leone Hopes U.N. Deploy Troops in Rebel Controlled Area Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leonean President Tejan
Kabbah has expressed the hope that U.N. peacekeepers would soon be
deployed throughout the country including the rebel-controlled
area, the state radio reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The returning of UNAMSIL (the U.N. peacekeeping force)
equipment by the RUF (Revolutionary United Front) is most welcome.
The government hopes the remaining equipment will soon be handed
over and that UNAMSIL will restart its deployment throughout the
country," Kabbah was quoted as saying on Thursday in Bumbuna, a
town about 160 kilometers northeast of Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The RUF rebels handed some seized U.N. vehicles back to the
UNAMSIL on Wednesday in an area about 120 kilometers northeast of
the capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
They had captured the vehicles in May when RUF fighters took
hundreds of U.N. peacekeepers hostage.
</P>
<P>
Much of the northern part of the country is still controlled by
the rebels, but Bumbuna has remained in the government hands
because a strong army presence has been maintained there to
protect a hydro-electric dam nearby.
</P>
<P>
The RUF, under new leader Issa Sesay, is showing signs of
willingness to renegotiate for peace under the Lome accord which
was supposed to end the war in July 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
