<DOCNO> XIE20000902.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC Denounces Iraqi Threats Against Kuwait, Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIYADH, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The foreign ministers of the
Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) Saturday strongly condemned the
Iraqi government's media campaign and threats against Kuwait and
Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
In a final communique of the 76th session of the ministerial
meeting held in Saudi coastal city of Jeddeh, the ministers said
the Iraqi government will not serve security and stability of the
Gulf region and nor did it want to learn from past lessons.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic group established in
1981, comprises Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the
United Arab Emirates. 
</P>
<P>
It also demanded the Iraqi government demonstrate good response
and cooperation towards the Security Council's resolution 1284 and
the U.N. Monitoring, Verification and Inspection Commission
(UNMOVIC), which replaced the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) last
December to supervise the elimination of Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under sweeping U.N. sanctions since 1990 imposed
shortly after it invaded its neighboring Kuwait and under relevant
U.N. resolutions, Iraq's eradication of weapons of mass destruction
is a prerequisite for lifting the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The arms inspections have been suspended since last December as
the defunct UNSCOM withdrew all its members from Iraq to escape U.
S. and British airstrikes against the country.
</P>
<P>
UNMOVIC is training its staff for possible continuation of
weapons inspections in Iraq which has so far refused the return of
the inspectors.
</P>
<P>
But the council underscored its well-known and firm position
towards the preservation of the independence of Iraq, its
territorial integrity and integration into the region.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has repeatedly launched verbal attacks on Saudi Arabia and
Kuwait, saying the two states are "partners in the crimes" against
Iraq because they provide bases for U.S. and British planes that
patrol a no-fly zone in southern Iraq and frequently attack targets
in the area. 
</P>
<P>
It also says Saudi Arabia and Kuwait are responsible for
prolonging the U.N. sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
