<DOCNO> XIE20000902.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian-Sudanese Committee Convenes First Session in Decade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of Egypt and
Sudan met here on Saturday for the first session in 10 years of the
Joint Egyptian-Sudanese Committee, signing eight cooperation
agreements.
</P>
<P>
In their inaugural speeches, Egypt's Amr Moussa and Sudan's
Mustafa Othman Ismail expressed confidence that the committee
meeting will open new ways for closer cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The two officials voiced hope that the two Arab neighbors will
join efforts to intensify their relations, Egypt's Middle East News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The committee was set to discuss rescheduling around 70 million
U.S. dollars of Sudanese debt to Egypt as well as measures to make
travel between the two countries easier. The two sides agreed to
pass on the matters to technical committees which were expected to
discuss them in detail in the coming week.
</P>
<P>
At the close of the session, Moussa and Ismail and other
officials of both sides signed eight agreements on cooperation in
agriculture, industry, wildlife, culture and tourism.
</P>
<P>
Ismail told reporters after the meeting that the committee
session crowned the process of normalization between the two Nile
Valley countries, saying that he hoped it would boost economic
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Egypt recalled its ambassador to Sudan after a June 1995
assassination attempt on Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in Addis
Ababa by Egyptian Islamists, in which Sudan was accused of
involvement.
</P>
<P>
But relations picked up in December 1999 after Sudanese Islamist
leader and former parliament speaker Hassan al-Turabi was sidelined
by President Omar al-Beshir.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has since appointed an ambassador to Sudan, Mohamed Assem,
who took office in Khartoum in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
