<DOCNO> XIE20000902.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Tunisia attracted investments worth 80 million dinars
(60 million U.S. dollars) in the first half of this year, making it
possible to construct 85 new factories including 16 major projects.
</P>
<P>
The total investments of the country rose to 612 million dinars
(450 million dollars) from 217 million dinars (160 million dollars)
during the same period in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The new investments created 4,500 jobs, 4,439 of which in the
mechanical and electrical sector.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The number of Internet subscribers in the United
Arab Emirates has risen to 160,000, while the number of users has
reached 400,000, according to statistics on Internet users in the
Arab world, compiled by Al Dabagh Information Technology Company
(DIT).
</P>
<P>
The volume of the UAE information technology market is estimated
to break the 2 billion dirhams (546.4 million dollars) barrier for
the first time at the end of 2000, with a growth level of around 20
percent, compared with 1999.
</P>
<P>
The report also predicted a jump in sales of personal computers
in the UAE.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The UAE Ministry of Health is planning to set up a
specialized centre for transfusion of blood, which will be of great
help in offering advance treatment for cancer patients, especially
those suffering from leukaemia and hereditary diseases like
thalassaemia.
</P>
<P>
The centre is expected to be completed in 18 months.
</P>
<P>
An area has been allocated for the project and international
experts in blood transfusion will run the centre and provide
training to doctors in the country.
</P>
<P>
The centre will be equipped with advanced medical equipment for
blood transfusion and related services and will provide treatment
to patients suffering from leukaemia and other blood diseases, the
report added.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Gulf Cooperation Council states are expected to
jointly establish a firm in the near future to oversee the setting
up of a common power grid aimed at catering to future demand for
electricity.
</P>
<P>
A common power grid for the GCC has been on the cards for a
while, with member states bringing the issue for discussion at
their yearly summit.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, running parallel to the power grid, GCC states have
also been backing a gas trunkline, which would supply natural gas
to consumers, mainly industrial and domestic, in member countries.
</P>
<P>
The project is piloted by the GCC secretariat general in Riyadh,
which has recently asked the GOIC to prepare a blueprint for the
project.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Istanbul Stock Exchange (IMKB) has launched a
drive to expand stock market in the ranks of the country's small-
and medium-sized (SME) enterprises.
</P>
<P>
IMKB Chairman Osman Birsen told reporters that IMKB does not
only create opportunities for large investors and companies but
also for people with smaller investments.
</P>
<P>
He said that a project aiming to get SMEs into the stock market
had been unfolded with the Organization for Economic Cooperation
and Development (OECD), and more than one SME could merge with
another larger unit in order to get into the IMKB.
</P>
<P>
IMKB is reportedly the fourth largest bourse in the world, with
850 million U.S. dollars in daily transactions.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Turkish state-owned Tugsas' fertilizer factory has
opened an international sell-off tender.
</P>
<P>
Some 25 large companies and five foreign firms have purchased
bidding documents for the sell-off.
</P>
<P>
Bagfas, a major Turkish private fertilizer producer, announced
in a statement on Friday that it had offered 65 million dollars to
bid for the tender.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- The price of oil in Cyprus goes up by one cent in
Cyprus pound (1.6 cents in dollars) per litre, following a
parliament decision Friday to adopt a proposal to this effect by
the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The price increase, which does not include value added tax, took
effect on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Petrol extra and unleaded petrol super now are sold at 45.1
cents (72.3 cents in dollars) per litre, petrol regular and
unleaded petrol at 43 cents (68.8 cents in dollars) per litre,
diesel regular and kerosene at 18.2 cents (29.1 cents in dollars)
and diesel of low sulphur content at 22.6 cents (36.2 cents in
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
