<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Defends Privatization Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa Saturday strongly defended the privatization policy
that his government is carrying out, saying it has greatly eased
the tax payers' burden.
</P>
<P>
Addressing hundreds of ruling Chama Cha Mapinduzi (CCM) members
and supporters at a presidential campaign rally in Tanzania's
eastern Morogoro Region, the CCM National Chairman said
privatization has managed to turn around in terms of profitability
several big state-owned companies on the verge of bankruptcy,
which are now contributing billions of shillings to government
coffers.
</P>
<P>
"Our intentions of establishing public-owned institutions were
aimed at generating revenue for the government, but experience
during the last three decades showed us that most of the public
firms were inefficient.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot continue going like this. Having people with little
knowledge and poor business acumen is dangerous for the economy.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot continue and trust people who have no financial
discipline to run the parastatals on our behalf," said Mkapa.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed as claims by opposition leaders that he is selling
off the country, saying Tanzania could not continue gambling in
its economic policies.
</P>
<P>
Elaborating on the economic successes achieved during his five-
year presidential term, Mkapa said Tanzania's economy is growing
at an average of 4 percent despite a series of odds such as floods
and droughts.
</P>
<P>
The shilling is stable as compared to major hard currencies,
and the government revenue collection has jumped from 29 billion
shillings (about 36.3 million U.S. dollars) monthly to an average
of 60 billion shillings (about 75 million U.S. dollars), he added.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa, who is seeking reelection for a second term during the
general elections to be held on October 29, appealed to Tanzanians
to protect economic and social gains made in the last five years
by voting for him.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania is now in the seventh year of privatization program.
Until last year, over 60 percent of all public enterprises were
privatized, or handed over to banks for loans recovery or
liquidation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
