<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians, Israel Unlikely to Reach Final Accord by Year End: Egyptian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said on Saturday that it is unlikely that the Palestinians
and Israel will be able to reach a final peace agreement by the end
of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Moussa told the Egyptian television that the Palestinians and
Israel will need as long as one year to negotiate the details of
the final peace accord after a framework agreement on the main
issues of the conflict is reached.
</P>
<P>
If the two sides are able to reach an agreement in the next
three months, before United States President Bill Clinton leaves
office, it will not be a "detailed, full and comprehensive
agreement," he said.
</P>
<P>
Rather, it would only cover the main and fundamental lines of
the thorny issues, including Israeli withdrawal, the exchange of
lands, the return of Palestinian refugees and the status of
Jerusalem, Moussa added.
</P>
<P>
"The time is not long enough" in the coming few weeks to reach a
detailed accord on all the subjects, so if the two sides could
agree on the main lines of the accord, that would also be "a good
thing," he said.
</P>
<P>
That framework accord, which will cover all the main issues such
as Jerusalem, Israeli troop withdrawals, refugees, security and
water issues, would be filled in with the details of a final peace
agreement, a process that "could take a year," the Egyptian
minister told the Egyptian television channel one.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that Egypt is hoping for such an agreement, but
admitted that there was still a possibility of failure.
</P>
<P>
He insisted the framework agreement must be balanced with
Palestinian sovereignty over East Jerusalem, warning that an
imbalanced accord would not last and would not lead to stability.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
