<HEADLINE> S. Leone Govt Rejects Negotiations With Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Sierra Leonean government
has ruled out the possibility of negotiations with the rebel group
known as the West Side Boys who are currently still holding seven
hostages, said a source reaching here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leonean Finance Minister James Jonah was quoted as
saying in Freetown, capital of the war-torn west African country,
that the government would not negotiate with the rebels for the
release of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
Jonah said the West Side Boys did not pose a military threat to
the government, they wanted to make political nuisance by taking
hostages. The government would, therefore, not give in to the
demands of the rebels they set for the release of their captives.
</P>
<P>
The abducted soldiers, 11 Britons and one Sierra Leonean, were
captured by the West Side Boys last Friday when they were
patrolling along the Freetown-Masiaka highway, and five British
soldiers were released on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The West Side Boys earlier set conditions for the release of
the remaining soldiers, demanding for a review of the Lome Peace
Accord, release of their supporters from prisons and reintegration
into the government army. 
</P>
