<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gene Linked to BBS Disorder in Newfoundland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Canadian scientists link a
disorder gene to an unusually high number of Newfoundlanders to be
born with extra fingers and toes, according to Saturday's National
Post newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The gene, which causes a complex disease called Bardet-Biedl
Syndrome (BBS), is held responsible for 30 to 35 people suffering
from the syndrome, which also includes obesity, blindness and
kidney failure.
</P>
<P>
The incidence is about 10 times higher than an average
worldwide, with a proportion of one in every 15,000 people in
Newfoundland against one in 160,000 elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Most of the half a million Newfoundlanders can trace their
family tree back to the first 20,000 settlers, Canadian scientists
say, with the conclusion that both parents must have one of the
genetic mistakes that cause BBS.
</P>
<P>
The new discovery is to be published in this month's issue of
Nature Genetics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
