<HEADLINE> Qatar Puts Forward Proposal to End Sufferings of Iraqi People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Qatar has offered written
proposals aimed at ending the sufferings of the Iraqi people who
have reeled under the 10-year-long U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The proposals were put forward during a meeting of the Gulf
foreign ministers, reports reaching here said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC)
states decided to study the ideals, said a final communique issued
at the end of the two-day meeting held in the western Saudi city of
Jeddah.
</P>
<P>
The communique of the GCC that groups Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman,
Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates (UAE) said the GCC
top diplomats hoped the Iraqi government would adopt serious
measures to abide by United Nations' resolutions to end the
sufferings of its people. But communique did revealed the contents
of the proposals.
</P>
<P>
U.N. imposed sweeping sanctions on Iraq shortly after it invaded
Kuwait in 1990 and put the elimination of its weapons of mass
destruction as a pre-requisite for lifting the embargo.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Foreign Minister Prince Saud Al-Faisal, who chaired the
meeting, also declined to disclose the details of the Qatari
ideals.
</P>
<P>
Al-Faisal said the Gulf governments would study these ideals
before presenting their notes on them. "I have nothing more to
add," he said.
</P>
<P>
Qatar made verbal proposals at the last GCC ministerial meeting,
but the foreign ministers demanded the ideals to be written.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the GCC foreign ministers urged Iraq to end
provocative media campaign against Kuwait and Saudi Arabia for
hosting the U.S. military bases.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also repeated regrets over Baghdad's refusal to
Arab and international initiatives for realizing an acceptable and
active mechanism, as part of cooperation with the United Nations to
lift the 10-year economic sanctions and end the sufferings of its
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
