<HEADLINE> Sulu Vice Gov. Appointed to Negotiate for American Hostage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
appointed Sulu Vice Governor Munib Estino Saturday to negotiate
for the release of an American hostage kidnapped by the Abu Sayyaf
in the south early this week.
</P>
<P>
Press Secretary Ricardo Puno said Estino's appointment would
mean that the certain Roland Sarmiento, supposedly tasked by the
government to negotiate for the release of Jeffrey Schilling, was
not duly authorized to do the job.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said the Abu Sayyaf had demanded Sarmiento
negotiate with them on the release of Schilling, who was abducted
in the southern city of Zamboanga last Monday and later
transferred to the rebels' camp in Jolo island, Sulu province.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old Schilling, who the rebels said is a spy of the
U.S. Central Intelligence Agency, was reportedly on a hunger
strike.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, who had earlier threatened to behead the American,
promised not to harm him while negotiations continue.
</P>
<P>
They also denied issuing demands for a ransom of 10 million U.S.
dollars for his release, saying they only asked that American food
and medicine be sent for Schilling who is said to have health
problems.
</P>
<P>
Abu Sayyaf rebels have released 17 hostages, but are still
holding two Finns, one French, one German and one Filipino of the
original group of 21 hostages kidnapped from Malaysia's resort
island of Sipadan on April 23, and two French journalists seized
in Jolo in July while covering the hostage crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
