<HEADLINE> Americans in Seoul Warned Against Possible Terrorist Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. embassy in Seoul on
Saturday asked U.S. citizens to exercise much greater caution for
their safety due to information on possible terrorist actions
against Americans in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. Embassy has received unconfirmed information that
terrorist actions by a non-Korean group may possibly be taken
against Americans, as well as U.S. government installations and/or
personnel in the Republic of Korea," the embassy said in a notice.
</P>
<P>
U.S. citizens in South Korea should review their own personal
security practices, be alert to any unusual activities around
their homes or businesses and report any significant incidents to
local police authorities, said the notice.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. embassy and U.S. military installations throughout
South Korea are taking steps to increase security at all
facilities.
</P>
<P>
In July, when strong anti-U.S. sentiments appeared in South
Korea after the United States Forces Korea acknowledged discharge
of poisonous chemicals into the Han River, the U.S. embassy issued
a travel warning for American citizens in the country, advising
them to stay alert and keep a low profile and avoid large crowds
when visiting commercial districts.
</P>
<P>
In August, the U.S. embassy has reportedly installed 10 super-
modern security cameras in the trees just outside its compound in
downtown Seoul. 
</P>
</TEXT>
