<HEADLINE> Cambodian Journalists Get Training on Economic Reporting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Some 20 Cambodian
journalists ended their three-day training Saturday on business
and economic reporting in Phnom Penh, which was co-sponsored by
the Club of Cambodian Journalists (CCJ) and the German Foundation
Konrad-Adenauer.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time for Cambodian journalists to get lectures
on business and economic reporting to improve their skills of
reporting on related issues although the economic and business
reporting is not so attractive to the readers in this war-torn
country.
</P>
<P>
The lectures were presented by two experienced journalists from
the Philippines who have covered economic and business reporting
for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
The participants at the three-day lectures were publishers,
editors and senior reporters in the country.
</P>
<P>
"I found the course was very significant and useful for
Cambodian journalists to be clear on how to have proper, accurate
and credible reporting on economic and business,'' said Puy Kea, a
reporter from Kyodo News who attended the course.
</P>
<P>
Puy Kea, who is also one of the leading members in the CCJ,
said his Club will introduce more training courses relating to
professional journalism in this country. 
</P>
