<HEADLINE> American Hostage in Philippines Said on Hunger Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- An American abducted by the Abu
Sayyaf in the southern Philippines reportedly went on a hunger
strike, a local TV station reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The ABS-CBN news channel said Jeffrey Schilling, who was
kidnapped by Abu Sayyaf rebels in Zamboanga city last Monday and
later transferred to their jungle lair in Jolo island, was on a
hunger strike.
</P>
<P>
The report can not be confirmed yet.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Abu Sayyaf spokesman Abu Sabaya Saturday denied
reports that they had demanded 10 million U.S. dollars in ransom
for the release of Schilling, whom they claim is an agent of the U.
S. Central Intelligence Agency.
</P>
<P>
He reportedly said they had only asked that American food and
medicine be sent for Schilling, who is said to have health
problems.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have agreed to start talks for the release of the 24-
year-old American and promised not to harm him while negotiations
continue.
</P>
<P>
In another development, another group of the Abu Sayyaf led by
Ghlib Andang, alias Commander Robot, has reportedly asked the
government to send a medical team to look after ailing Wilde
Almeda, who led a group of 12 Filipino Christian evangelists to
the rebels camp in Jolo in early July to pray for the hostages
seized from Malaysia's resort island of Sipadan in April.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said the group of evangelists were also taken
hostage by the Abu Sayyaf, but the rebels said they could leave
anytime if they wish.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf has released 17 hostages but is still holding
one Filipino and six Europeans, including two French journalists
seized in Jolo in July.
</P>
<P>
Philippine government chief negotiator Robert Aventajado
expressed optimism Saturday that they would be freed in a few days.
</P>
</TEXT>
