<DOCNO> XIE20000902.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand, Russia Agree to Promote Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Russia have
agreed to cooperate in promoting tourism between the two countries,
the Thai News Agency (TNA) said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Wanwilai Promlakhano, deputy director of the Department of
Policy and Planning of the Bangkok Metropolitan Administration (
BMA) said that she and representatives of the Tourism Authority of
Thailand (TAT) met the Russian tourism authorities and
representatives of 50 travelling firms in Moscow to exchange
information and opinions on tourism promotion between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed problems of tourism faced by the countries
and ways to address the problems, which will lead to increase in
tourist arrivals in Bangkok and Moscow, she said.
</P>
<P>
Wanwilai led a Thai delegation to visit Moscow in late August
to organize a tourism project, dubbed "the Bangkok Days in Moscow"
at a cultural center, aimed to open a new market and promote Thai
tourism in the country.
</P>
<P>
A main problem of attracting more Russian arrivals in Bangkok
was the language barrier and shortages of experienced guides who
can speak Russian fluently, she pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The BMA was considering to employ some Russian people who stay
in Thailand on a temporary basis, and train them to be part-time
guides for Russian tourists, as the number of Russian arrivals in
Thailand normally increases in the last four months of every year,
she said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the TAT forecast that the number of Russian arrivals
in Thailand would increase to 70,000 this year from 50,000 in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
