<HEADLINE> Myanmar Opposition Leader Brought Back Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar opposition party leader
Aung San Suu Kyi was brought back home by the authorities Saturday
morning from Dala, the area where she had been barred from
travelling further after she stayed there for eight days, a
government statement said here Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The official Information sheet said all others who accompanied
Aung San Suu Kyi, general secretary of the National League for
Democracy (NLD), were also sent back respectively.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time for the Myanmar authorities to manage
to end the incident in a way similar to that taken in the last
incident which took place in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
The statement described the NLD leader's return as being "
escorted back" in a motorcade facilitated by the government.
</P>
<P>
The action was taken when the NLD was urging the government to
lift travel ban on their leaders to continue their journey and
complaining about the poor living conditions by staying on the
roadside.
</P>
<P>
So far, the NLD has not yet officially commented on the latest
incident.
</P>
<P>
Aung San Suu Kyi, along with three other NLD leaders totaling
more than a dozen, was barred for security reason from travelling
further after she arrived at Dala in Yangon division last Thursday
en-route to Gungyangon and Kawmu areas in the same division to
meet her party members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
