<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Olympic Tennis Team Wants Former Coach Re-appointed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The South African Olympic
tennis team has recently en masse signed a document requesting the
National Olympic Committee of South Africa (NOCSA) to re-appoint
Charlton Eagle as their coach for the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
Eagle was replaced by acting chief executive of the South
African Tennis Association (SATA) Mohammed Sheik, but only in a
managerial capacity as Sheik has no coaching experience.
</P>
<P>
NOCSA wrote to SATA in August, stating that Eagle "had failed
thus far to attend to critical matters" and recommended that Sheik
take over the duties.
</P>
<P>
The letter also made it clear that the final choice on who will
manage or coach the South African Olympic tennis team rests with
NOCSA.
</P>
<P>
However, the South African tennis players are now requesting
NOCSA to "re-examine the current circumstances pertaining to the
role of Charlton Eagle with our Olympic tennis team".
</P>
<P>
The document, signed by South Africa's Fed Cup captain Eagle,
Davis Cup captain Craig Tiley, Wayne Ferreira, Amanda Coetzer,
Liezel Horn,David Adams, John-Laffnie de Jager and SATA player
representative Michael de Jongh, said that while they all have no
problem with Sheik as manager of the team, they did feel they
needed a coach.
</P>
<P>
"The coaching involves scouting, practice plans, emotional
support,on-court advice and strategy advice. Mr Eagle will make a
difference in all of these areas," the document stressed.
</P>
<P>
Speaking from New York, Eagle said he had been aware that there
were certain requirements a manager had to meet as far as
attending meetings and camps are concerned, but that as he was
appointed as coach of the team, he did not have the same
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
"If I had been told it was a prerequisite for being coach of
the team I would have made a plan to travel to South Africa. I was
never informed that this was a stipulation," Eagle added.
</P>
<P>
In their letter to SATA, a copy of which was forwarded to Eagle,
NOCSA stated that they took "into consideration all aspects of the
tennis players' requirements and the manager's interaction with
NOCSA management". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000902.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heyns Possible to Repeat Historic Exploits at Sydney Olympic Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 2 (Xinhuaz) -- South African double
Olympic champion Penny Heyns will return to Sydney carrying the
hopes of the continent for a repeat of her historic exploits there
last year.
</P>
<P>
Following her stunning form at 1996 Atlanta Olympic Games, in
which she broke two world records, an Olympic record and won two
Olympic gold medals in the 100m and 200m breaststroke, Heyns
struggled in 1997 and 1998 and began to despair that she would
never again be a major force in world swimming.
</P>
<P>
She began to slide down the world rankings after parting from
long-time coach Jan Bidrman, who moved to Calgary at the beginning
of 1997 to coach the Canadian national squad, while Heyns remained
behind in Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
But after failing to win any medals at the 1998 world
championships in Perth, Australia and withdrawing from the
Commonwealth Games in Kuala Lumpur, Heyns decided to rejoin
Bidrman.
</P>
<P>
"I packed my bags and went to Calgary to join up with Jan and
just got back into it. I now believe the disappointments of 1998
are starting to work for me," said Heyns.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 Pan Pacific Championships were a turning point for the
Durban-born swimmer, who didn't come home empty-handed with
clocking world records in the 50m, 100m and 200m (twice).
</P>
<P>
However the comeback was not without some controversy after
Heyns admitted using the controversial food supplement creatine.
</P>
<P>
"Creatine is not a stimulant. I am simply using it to improve
my diet," said Heyns, adding that she was only using the protein
supplement in small doses because she was scared that it could be
habit-forming or that she may become psychologically dependent on
it.
</P>
<P>
Although she has recently failed to deliver anything close to
her incredible form of last year Heyns remains strong favourite
for another double in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's head swimming coach Wayne Riddin is also
expecting medals from the breaststroke star.
</P>
<P>
"Penny swam a 1:08 (100m breaststroke) at the Canadian
championships, so her form's coming back. Her 50m and 100m swims
are what's important. She hasn't eased up yet," the coach said.
</P>
<P>
However, Riddin remained cautious, saying: "Olympic year is a
funny year. To predict anything at Olympics is foolish." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
