<HEADLINE> Indonesia Agrees to Extend Aceh Cease-Fire Accord Temporarily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
agreed in principle to extend a three-month cease-fire accord with
the rebel Free Aceh Movement (GAM) which expires Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Coordinating Minister for Political, Social and Security
Affairs Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono told reporters here Saturday that
President Abdurrahman Wahid has approved the temporary extension
of the cease-fire -- the Joint Understanding on Humanitarian Pause.
</P>
<P>
But the minister gave no time frame for the extension.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia has agreed to extend the humanitarian pause in
principle. The president has agreed for the temporary extension
while we are waiting for a definitive consensus with GAM," Susilo
said after meeting with the president.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed in Geneva on May 12 for a three-month
cease-fire aimed at ending over two decades of violence in the
resource-rich northwestern province and alleviating the
humanitarian situation there.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Indonesian government and the GAM
agreed to reduce tension and stop violence in the province.
</P>
<P>
Rebels in Aceh have been fighting for 25 years for independence,
a greater share of oil profits, and the right to imposing Islamic
religious laws. Thousands have been killed in decades of fighting
between Indonesian security forces and Aceh rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
