<HEADLINE> Manila Extends Legal Aid to Overseas Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and a
private lawyers' group have dispatched a joint team abroad to
determine legal aid requirements of overseas Filipino workers (
OFWs) and firm up a joint assistance program for them.
</P>
<P>
The joint team will go to OFW destinations such as Rome, Jeddah,
Athens and Riyadh to conduct a first-hand survey of the conditions
of OFWs in these cities, Undersecretary Benjamin Domingo of the
Department of Foreign Affairs said on a radio program over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
"We will make a complete survey," Domingo said.
</P>
<P>
Promoting the welfare of OFWs is one of the pillars of the
government's foreign policy, alongside economic diplomacy and
national security.
</P>
<P>
Some 800,000 Filipinos leave their country every year to seek
jobs abroad and there are now about 5.5 million OFWs, government
officials said. But the figures don't include undocumented
Filipino workers.
</P>
<P>
It is estimate that the number of OFWs exceeds seven who remit
home around seven billion U.S. dollars every year, a major source
of the country's foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
Domingo said that since the Philippines has one of the highest
number of overseas workers, it must have the corresponding
mechanisms to help them.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement with the government, the Integrated Bar of
the Philippines, which boasts of 40,000 private lawyers, agreed to
help handle OFWs' cases abroad and also link up with lawyers'
associations in host countries concerned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
