<HEADLINE> Lebanese Civilians Beaten by Israeli Soldiers along Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A Lebanese civilian was beaten
by Israeli soldiers at the border on Sheikh Abbad hill after he
attempted to remove a plaque inscribed in Hebrew, the Daily Star
newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It quoted sources, a squad of Hezbollah observers on Abbad, as
claiming that Ghanaian U.N. peacekeeper soldiers positioned at the
summit of the hill failed to intervene.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) said it had in on
knowledge of such an incident.
</P>
<P>
The witnesses said the assault occurred on Thursday evening when
Mahmoud Abdel-Rhaman Sabbagh, 26, was hit several times with a
rifle butt when he and other civilians tried to remove two stone
plaques fastened to a wall on the Lebanese side of the border.
</P>
<P>
The border runs along the summit of the hill and bisects an
ancient tomb revered by Muslims and Jews. Israeli soldiers are
stationed to the east of the tomb in front of a new outpost.
</P>
<P>
Sabbagh reportedly received bruises to his back and shoulder.
</P>
<P>
The witnesses said that the Ghanaians had attempted to stop the
Lebanese from removing the plaques but gave up when Sabbagh and his
comrades refused to leave.
</P>
<P>
The peacekeepers moved away from the hilltop shrine to their
post 50 meters away, allowing the Israeli soldiers to step across
the unfenced border and beat Sabbagh, the witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, civilians were allowed to roam the hilltop and were
not prevented from approaching the border by Ghanaian UNIFIL
troops.
</P>
<P>
UNIFIL spokesman Timur Goksel said he had received "no reports
of any such activity occurring at Abbad." 
</P>
</TEXT>
