<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Istanbul to Toughen Measures on Bilge Water Discharge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Turkish authorities were
preparing strict inspection of bilge waters released from ships
transiting Bosporus and Dardanelles Straits linking the Black Sea
and the mediterranean Sea, Turkish Daily News reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The initiative was taken jointly by the Istanbul Directorate for
Environment and the Borders and Coastlines Health Directorate,
aiming at curbing the increasing pollution in the Marmara Sea.
</P>
<P>
Istanbul Provincial Environment Director Yavuz Cengel said that
some 12 percent of the pollution in the Marmara Sea comes from
freely-emptied bilge waters from ships passing the straits.
</P>
<P>
The authorities will use both helicopters and satellite to
monitor ships to empty their bilge systems safely in specifically-
designed facilities.
</P>
<P>
Cengel said that "ships will be able to off-load their bilge
systems and solid waste in Istanbul in specific locations at the
entrance points to the straits. Any ship refuses to do so will be
fined." However, he did not mention the amount of fines to be
imposed on violators.
</P>
<P>
The bilge water and waste will be recycled, he added.
</P>
<P>
The project, still being drawn up, will be submitted to the
ministries of Health and Environment. In stage two of the project,
the levels of pollution in the Black Sea will also be tested.
</P>
<P>
Cengel said that "the only way to enter the Black Sea is via the
Bosporus. Any vessel that enters the Black Sea must be inspected on
its return journey with the cooperation of all Black Sea
countries."
</P>
<P>
Cengel also blamed waste water discharged from factories for the
pollution of the Marmara Sea. Once the level of hazardous chemicals
in industrial discharge is reduced and the bilge inspection project
enforced, the sea will see lower levels of pollution within five to
10 years.
</P>
<P>
"The Marmara Sea is not beyond saving. This is why such a system
is imperative," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000902.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Move Naval Headquarters Away from Earthquake Belt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish military will move
its naval headquarters from Golcuk in the Marmara region to Izmir
on the Aegean Sea, reported Turkish Daily News on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made in view of the devastating earthquake,
which hit the Marmara region on August 17, 1999. Golcuk was among
the cities suffering the heaviest damages in the quake that killed
17,000 people.
</P>
<P>
According to the decision, the Navy's main base will also be
moved from Golcuk to Aksaz of Marmaris, Mugla province, on the
Aegean Sea.
</P>
<P>
After a year of search for an ideal location, Chief of the
General Staff Huseyin Kivrikoglu and Vice Admiral Lihami Erdil
announced recently that the Navy will be relocated in the Aegean
region.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Turkish naval submarines and ships have been billeted
at Eregli on the Black Sea and at Aksaz in Marmaris.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, some naval institutions such as its
hospitals, logistical support units and shipyards will remain in
Golcuk.
</P>
<P>
The new naval headquarters building will be constructed in
Yenikale in the Inciralti district of Izmir, southwest of Turkey,
and the Navy plans to complete the move into it within the next
year.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is a known earthquake-prone country, which stretches
along three established major fault lines.
</P>
<P>
Turkish and international experts have predicted that another
strong earthquake measuring above seven degrees on the Richter
scale will be most likely to happen in the Marmara region.
</P>
<P>
Golcuk is believed to lie on the top of a very active seismic
zone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
