<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar's Value Linked with Knowledge Economy: Economist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian government's
chief scientific adviser Robin Batterham said Saturday Australia's
economic performance was closely linked to how well it performed
as a knowledge economy.
</P>
<P>
According to the Australian Associated Press, Batterham said
the decline of the value of the Australian dollar was inevitable
unless Australia dramatically lifted support for science and
research and development.
</P>
<P>
"The rate of knowledge increase will actually increase the rate
of fall of commodity prices and hence the Australian dollar. We
won't have to wait 30 years. We'll see it a lot sooner than that,"
he warned.
</P>
<P>
Figures released this week showed that the growth of gross
expenditure on research and development in the country had fallen
behind the rate of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
He criticized that the thesis that science, engineering and
technology were essential foundations of innovation and the
knowledge economy was not widely accepted in the community.
</P>
<P>
"When I look at our present path, I look at the halving of the
Australian dollar over the last 30 years," the economist said.
</P>
</TEXT>
