<HEADLINE> Kenyan Courts in Dilemma over AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The AIDS scourge has started
affecting the administration of justice as more convicts state in
their mitigation pleas that they are HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
This has put the judiciary in a dilemma since the law does not
say how courts should handle AIDS patients, High Court Judge Joyce
Aluoch was quoted by Kenya's major newspaper Daily Nation as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Judge Aluoch advised the magistrates on Saturday in a seminar
to ensure justice is not compromised by using their discretion to
decide wisely on cases involving AIDS victims.
</P>
<P>
"It has become quite common for convicted AIDS-infected people
to invoke their sickly status. But you have to be careful and
ensure your decision agrees with judicial principles," said Aluoch.
</P>
<P>
The east African country has been ravaged by the AIDS pandemic
with an infection rate of 14 percent among the people aged between
15 to 49. 
</P>
