<HEADLINE> Kenya Factories Drive up Sugar Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The crisis in Kenya's sugar
industry worsened Saturday when two major sugar factories
announced a price rise despite a continued fall in production.
</P>
<P>
Sony, one of the leading ffactories, announced a 39 percent
rise, bringing ex-factory prices from a 50kg bag to 2,705
shillings (about 36 dollars), up form 1,950 shillings (about 26
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The market demand for the commodity has exceeded the production,
which has dropped by 90 percent in the factory due to the acute
shortage of cane, Sony's acting general manager Charles Kanjagara
said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is being worsened by unscrupulous wholesalers
who are conspiring to smuggle the commodity at exorbitant prices
to retail outlets in Tanzania," Kanjagara claimed.
</P>
<P>
As the shortage continues to bite, consumers in Nairobi started
queuing outside supermarkets, which usually opens door from 8:30
am, from as early as 6 a.m..
</P>
<P>
The El Nino rains in 1997 and 1998 damaged almost all sugar
plantations in Kenya and it takes two years for sugarcanes to
mature.
</P>
<P>
The sugar shortage is expected to last for six months,
according to the prediction of the agriculture ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
