<HEADLINE> Oldest Surviving Olympian Open Sydney Village </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The first group of 2,000
athletes entered Olympic village on Saturday when 93-year-old Edie
Payne, Australia's oldest surviving Olympian, officially opened
the village at the main Sydney Games site Saturday as the first 2,
000 competitors took residence.
</P>
<P>
The wheelchair bound Mrs. Payne, a sprinter at the 1928
Amsterdam Games, broke down and cried after welcoming the athletes
and officials.
</P>
<P>
About 8,000 more over the next 10 days prior to the opening
ceremonies on September 15.
</P>
<P>
There will also be 5,000 officials in residence from 199
countries and regions as well as the territory of East Timor. They
will be looked after by a staff of 7,000 mostly volunteers.
</P>
<P>
The first national group in Saturday were athletes from Finland,
followed by those from Cuba and Belarus.
</P>
<P>
The 350 million US dollars village became New South Wales state
's fifth-largest city with its official opening. Olympic officials
say it is the first time in the history of the Summer Games that
one building has had the capacity to accommodate all competitors
in the same location.
</P>
<P>
The athletes at Homebush Bay will be housed in 1,000 new houses
and apartments in the same general area as 13 venues hosting 17
sports. Services for the athletes include a supermarket, post
office, bank, florist, travel agency, medical center and disco.
</P>
<P>
The main dining hall will serve 60,000 meals a day.
</P>
<P>
The village will become the Sydney suburb of Newington after
the Games. The apartments and houses will be sold for prices
ranging from 290,000 to 600,000 Australian dollars (174,000 to 360,
000 US dollar). 
</P>
</TEXT>
