<HEADLINE> Manila Hopeful of Resumption of Talks with MILF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
optimistic over the resumption of peace talks with the Moro
Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) following reports that the
secessionist group plans to reconstitute its peace team.
</P>
<P>
Edgardo Batenga, chairman of the government peace panel,
disclosed Saturday in a radio interview that reconstitution of the
MILF team was the result of weeks of back-door negotiations with
the MILF Central committee.
</P>
<P>
The MILF earlier withdrew all authority to its peace panel to
negotiate a peace agreement with the government in the wake of a
series of clashes with government troops in the southern island of
Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
"They will reconstitute the membership of the advisory panel
and the technical committee when the time is right as they
perceive. I strongly believe the time will be sooner than later,"
Batenga said.
</P>
<P>
He said communication lines remain open between the government
panel and the central leadership of the separatist group, which
has been fighting for more than two decades for a independent
Islamic state in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
"In accordance with the national peace policy, we have to
resolve the armed conflict in Mindanao through peaceful settlement.
A solution is imperative for a just, lasting and comprehensive
peace in Mindanao," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The war in Mindanao this year has claimed more than 1,300 lives,
including those of over 300 civilians, caused damage worth 89
million pesos (about 2 million U.S. dollars), and displaced some
450,000 people, according to a military report.
</P>
<P>
And the military has spent more than 1.3 billion pesos (about
29 million dollars) in pushing an offensive against forces of the
MILF.
</P>
<P>
Batenga said the government, on its part, is looking forward
towards attaining the environment necessary for the peace process
to proceed with the MILF.
</P>
<P>
He said the cabinet Cluster E, which deals with national
security concerns and political affairs, has instructed his panel
to make sure that the peace process with the MILF move forward.
</P>
<P>
"It is the desire of the government to pursue the peace process.
A sincere and final resolution of the final conflict must be done
through negotiation," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
