<HEADLINE> Power Cut in Kenya Could Extend to April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Energy Minister Francis
Masakhalia warns Kenyans that the current power rationing could
last until next April if the anticipated short rains in October
fails.
</P>
<P>
However, if the rains forecast by the Meteorological Department
is realized, the power rationing would ease accordingly,
Masakhalia was quoted by Kenya's leading newspaper Daily Nation as
saying.
</P>
<P>
If the rainy season arrives in October but with inadequate
rainfall, Kenyans should expect power rationing to continue at
reduced levels until the onset of the long rains next April,
Masakhalia said Saturday when attending a ceremony for the
installation of an emergency generating unit.
</P>
<P>
With the support of the World Bank, Kenya will introduce three
emergency fuel generating units of European firms in September and
October to reduce the power deficit.
</P>
<P>
The power shortage in the east African country has led to a
loss of over 2 million U.S. dollars since last September when the
rationing was adopted, according to local newspaper Standard.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the World Bank Country Director to Kenya, Harold
Wackman, said the bank is likely to provide a credit of 75 million
U.S. dollars to meet Kenya's cost in purchasing power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
