<HEADLINE> AIDS Scientist Seeks Partnership With Ugandan Counterpart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- French Scientist Luc Montagnier,
who discovered the AIDS virus, said he is ready to establish a
partnership with Ugandan AIDS scientists to address the epidemic
in Africa, the New Vision daily reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Montagnier said the partnership would look for cheaper AIDS
treatment strategies and vaccines, and establish the factors that
fuel the epidemic in Sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said he was surprised by the high rates of heterosexual HIV
transmission in the region, which was higher than that in
developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Anti--retroviral drugs were not affordable in Africa and it was
the responsibility of scientists to design cheaper treatment, said
Montagnier.
</P>
<P>
"The drug companies are willing to reduce the prices. We can
also reduce the cost of treatment by reducing the duration of
treatment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Minister in the Prime Minister's Office Mondo Kagonyera said
Uganda was privileged to host Hontagnier, and would benefit from
his knowledge and experience. 
