<HEADLINE> China: Top of the Week (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
national news Xinhua released from August 26 to September 1:
</P>
<P>
-- Experts to a symposium held in Beijing on August 26 urged to
make a special law to govern the activities in the development of
the underdeveloped west China, while calling on concerned local
governments to attach greater importance to environmental
protection.
</P>
<P>
-- The Taiwan leader's delay in deciding whether to assume the
chairmanship of the "National Unification Council" shows that he
is still evading the "one China" principle and that he has not
essentially changed his support for "Taiwan independence", said a
Xinhua commentary published on August 27.
</P>
<P>
-- Japanese Foreign Minister Yohei Kono arrived in Beijing on
August 28 on a four-day official visit to China, at the invitation
of Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese industrial enterprises saw their economic efficiency
surge to the highest level over the past few years as total
profits topped 200 billion yuan (24 billion US dollars) during the
first seven months of this year.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by the National Bureau of
Statistics (NBS) on August 29, the complex index of industrial
efficiency jumped 16.6 points year-on-year to 111.3 points for the
first seven months of the year. The index was 1.9 points higher
than it was for the January-June period.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao announced in
Beijing on August 29 that President Fernando de la Rua of the
Republic of Argentina will pay a state visit to China from
September 10-14 at the invitation of Chinese President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
-- Over nine million civil servants in China have received
training over the past seven years, according to sources from the
Ministry of Personnel.
</P>
<P>
-- The State Development Planning Commission (SDPC) will send
inspectors to check state key projects on their legality, quality,
finance and management, according to a newly released government
decree.
</P>
<P>
-- China's top three airlines, Air China, China Eastern
Airlines and China Southern Airlines, became profitable in the
first half of this year, according to statistics from the General
Administration of Civil Aviation of China (CAAC) released on
August 29.
</P>
