<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, September 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Interamerican Development Bank (IDB) Chairman
Enrique Iglesias called on the South American countries Friday to
surmount all the pending challenges to achieve the regional
integration.
</P>
<P>
Iglesias suggested at the on-going South American summit that
the countries concerned arrive at clear and transparent agreements
for attraction of long-term investment and improvement of South
American exports. Iglesias identified the challenges as regulation
of infrastructure services, maintenance of macroeconomic policies,
reduction of risks to private enterprises interested in
infrastructure, and wider cooperation in services improvement. (
SAmerica-IDB-Challenges)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Dominican President Hipolito Mejia said Friday
that his country is planning to improve economic ties with
countries in the Central American and Caribbean region, according
to a report from Santo Domingo, capital of Dominica.
</P>
<P>
The export of Dominica goods to the Central American and
Caribbean region accounts for a small portion in its total sales
abroad in 1999 which amounted to 5.203 billion U.S. dollars, Mejia
said at the annual meeting of the Caribbean Society of Food
Cultivation (CSFC). The Caribbean islands market must be "tied up"
for the products of Dominica, Mejia added. (Dominica-CAmerica-
Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazilian President Fernando Henrique Cardoso
Friday reaffirmed the creation of a free trade area between the
Southern Common Market (Mercosur) and the Community of Andean
Nations (CAN) by January of 2002.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso made the remarks during a summit meeting of South
American countries. The 12 presidents, who participated in the two-
day summit that ended Friday, signed the "Brasilia Communique"
pledging to create free trade between South America's two main
trade blocs as soon as possible, bringing together 340 million
people in an area with a combined economic output of 1.3 trillion
U.S. dollars. (Brazil-Free Trade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUCHAREST -- Farm production will face a setback this year,
said Romanian Prime Minister Mugur Isarescu here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"This will seriously influence the fulfillment of national
economic growth goals," he said. Romania this year is suffering
the worst drought in a century. "This has caused a 20 percent
decrease in farm production, or a loss of 500 million U.S. dollars,
or possibly even 1 billion dollars compared with an average bumper
harvest year," said the Romanian leader. Agricultural production
counts for 15 percent of Romania's gross domestic product. (
Romania-Agriculture) 
</P>
</TEXT>
