<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Solemnly Celebrates 55th National Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam Saturday morning
celebrated its 55th National Day in the capital Hanoi by grand
military and mass parades.
</P>
<P>
Before the mammoth military and mass parades in Ba Dinh square,
Vietnamese President Tran Duc Luong gave his speech reviewing the
country's 55-year history.
</P>
<P>
He said that Vietnam's strategic goals are national
independence, territorial unification and integrity, freedom,
democracy, welfare for the people, and a just, advanced, united
and humane society, and the country's wish to befriend all nations
and peoples in the world for the sake of peace, national
independence, democracy and social progress.
</P>
<P>
Luong added that the Doi Moi (Renovation) cause launched by
Vietnamese Communist Party in its 6th Congress in 1986 lifted the
country out of socio-economic crisis and ushered in a new stage of
development. The country's economy has seen relatively high growth
and development. The material and spiritual life of the people has
been significantly improved and the face of the country is
changing with every passing day.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese President stressed that it is strategic tasks of
Vietnamese Party, State and people in the coming 21st century to
continue the Doi Moi process, intensify industrialization and
modernization, successfully realize the goals of rich people,
strong country, just, democratic and advanced society, firmly
safeguard the Fatherland of socialist Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
After Luong's speech, military and mass parades began. 17,000
of Vietnamese army officials and soldiers from across the country
participated in the military parade. About 3,000 artists from art
troupes at both professional and grassroots levels joined together
at an artists' parade.
</P>
<P>
According to a schedule, in the evening spectacular fireworks
will light up the skies above various historic sites of the
country marking the National Day, including Dien Bien Phu, Tan
Trao, Hanoi, Buon Ma Thuot, Ho Chi Minh City and Can Tho. 
</P>
</TEXT>
