<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Opposition Leader Denies Awareness of Assassination Attempt on President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's main opposition
leader has denied charges by President Chandrika Kumaratunga that
he was aware of the details of the last December assassination
attempt on her life, describing it as a smear to his name at the
start of the general elections campaign.
</P>
<P>
In his letter to President Kumaratunga dated August 31, Ranil
Wickremesinghe, leader of the main opposition United National
Party (UNP) said that he denied this "false allegation completely.
"
</P>
<P>
He accused Kumaratunga of choosing to challenge him publicly at
the start of the general elections campaign in the hope that she
might be able to smear his name.
</P>
<P>
"Even worse you have decided to do this whilst using your
Presidential immunity against prosecution," he added.
</P>
<P>
Ranil said that Kumaratunga made a similar allegation last
March in the Far Eastern Economic Review and the President stated
in a later meeting between them that she had been quoted out of
context.
</P>
<P>
He also blamed Kumaratunga on the rising living cost due to the
recent depreciation of rupee, the small island country's currency
and the slowness of the economic development in the country.
</P>
<P>
However, the official Daily News newspaper quoted in recent
days the International Herald Tribune as saying that the Gross
Domestic Product (GDP) of Sri Lanka grew six percent in the first
half of this year on rising exports, garments and tea. It
demonstrated that the country's economy is expanding despite the
on-going 17 year ethnic war between government forces and
separatist Tamil Tiger rebels.
</P>
<P>
While addressing the Uva Province convention of her Sri Lanka
Freedom Party last Wednesday, President Kumaratunga charged that
Ranil was aware of details of the assassination attempt on her
life during last December presidential elections campaign.
</P>
<P>
The President challenged Ranil to deny this allegation publicly
and clear his name, if the allegation was false.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga narrowly escaped an assassination attempt but lost
her vision in her right eye on December 18 last year when a Tamil
Tiger woman suicide bomber struck after an election rally in Town
Hall.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's 11th Parliamentary election is to be held on
October 10. Among the 45 recognized political parties to contest
for a 225-member Parliament seats, the main rivals are the ruling
People's Alliance and UNP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
