<HEADLINE> Myanmar, Thailand to Promote Tourism Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar and Thailand held a
meeting here on Friday on promotion of cooperation in the
development of tourism industry between the two countries,
official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by Major-General Saw Lwin, Myanmar
Minister of Hotels and Tourism, and Adisai Bodharamik, visiting
Thai Minister at the Prime Minister's Office and Chairman of the
Thai Tourism Authority.
</P>
<P>
The 20-member Thai delegation, led by Adisai, arrived here on
Friday morning for the meeting at the invitation of Saw Lwin.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar and Thailand initiated an accord on cooperation in
tourism in July 1998 and since then Myanmar has launched two
tourism fairs in Bangkok respectively in September 1998 and 1999,
aimed at attracting more tourists from Thailand to Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Thailand plays a key role in supplying tourists to Myanmar
among Myanmar's neighboring countries and ranks the second after
Japan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of Thai hotel investment projects signed
with Myanmar has gone to eight with a total investment amounting
to 210 million U.S. dollars, according to the Myanmar tourism
authorities.
</P>
<P>
Other official statistics show that a total of 246,007 foreign
tourists visited Myanmar in fiscal year 1999-2000, which ended in
March, 41,387 or 14.4 percent less than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Myanmar has absorbed so far 1.1 billion dollars of
contracted foreign investment in more than 40 projects in the
sector of hotels and tourism since the country opened to such
investment in late 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
