<DOCNO> XIE20000902.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Follow Path Best Suited to Own Conditions: Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar will continue to follow
the path best suited to its own conditions, relying on its own
resources, Myanmar leader Lieutenant-General Khin Nyunt was quoted
by Saturday's official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Speaking here on Friday at the opening of the country's first
ever training course in diplomatic skills for senior officials
conducted by the foreign ministry, Khin Nyunt, first secretary of
the Myanmar State Peace and Development Council, said Myanmar
wishes to have friendly relations will all countries in keeping
with its independent and active foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
"We have developed increasingly good cooperative relations with
liked-minded countries," he noted, "however, today some countries
are exerting all kinds of pressure on Myanmar in their efforts to
cast it in their own mold."
</P>
<P>
He charged these countries with openly interfering in Myanmar's
internal affairs without naming them.
</P>
<P>
He accused these countries of using every pretext from forced
labor and narcotic drugs to health and education conditions to do
so.
</P>
<P>
He warned that Myanmar will never bow to such pressure.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for Myanmar to participate more actively
and effectively in international arena in order to safeguard its
national interest and promote friendship and cooperation with like-
minded countries particularly with neighboring countries and those
in the region.
</P>
<P>
He added that Myanmar had diplomatic relations with only 67
countries before the present government took office in late 1988,
disclosing that the number of such countries has gone up to 85 and
will still grow to 100 in the very near future.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, with the establishment of
diplomatic relations with 85 countries throughout the world,
Myanmar has opened 30 embassies and two consulates there, while in
Myanmar, embassies of 27 nations, offices of five U.N. agencies
and two consulates have been opened.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar, in addition to being a member of the United Nations,
is also a member of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations and
the BIMST-EC, another regional economic grouping comprising
Bangladesh, India, Myanmar, Sri Lanka and Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
