<HEADLINE> Colombian President Calls for Peaceful Talks With Guerrillas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Conflicts with guerrillas
should be solved through peaceful talks with the help of foreign
countries, said Colombian President Andres Pastrana here Friday.
</P>
<P>
At the South American Summit attended by the presidents of all
the South American countries, Pastrana said it doesn't mean
foreign military intervention in the peace process, and promised
that there is no civil war in his country.
</P>
<P>
"Colombia will never be a Vietnam," he said.
</P>
<P>
The conflicts with guerrillas in the country have dragged on
for 40 years, said the president. "Now it is time to seek a
settlement with the guerrillas through peaceful talks," he added.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana also mentioned the environmental pollution caused by
toxic chemicals discharged into rivers by local residents during
the cultivation, processing or trafficking of drugs.
</P>
<P>
He said he will discuss the issue with European Union delegates
in October to seek alternatives solutions for local residents
involved in drug-trafficking.  
</P>
</TEXT>
