<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru Denies Purchase of Weapons From Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Peruvian Army is again
denying that no member of their armed forces involved in the
purchase of military weapons from Jordan, Defense Minister General
Carlos Bergamino said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Peru announced last week that it had smashed a ring that flew
10,000 Kalashnikov rifles from Jordan to Colombian rebels, which
has lead to a diplomatic impasse between Peru and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The Peruvian government asserts that the purchase was made by a
gang of international traffickers.
</P>
<P>
Supporting the government's earlier statements, Bergamino said
there is no general by the name of Lucio Olivera in Peru's armed
forces. He claimed it is a fictitious name used by someone who
reportedly made the purchase on behalf of the Peruvian Army.
</P>
<P>
"One of the documents the Jordanian authorities have exhibited
to prove the legitimacy of the sale of 10,000 rifles to Peru has
the signature of 'General Olivera,' which tends to indicate the
traffickers deceived the Jordanians," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bergamino concluded by stating that the acquisition of weapons
in Peru must have the approval of the National Defense Council and
the purchase will be made through the bank of state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
