<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian President Denies Seeking Hegemony in S. America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso denied that his country intends to play a
hegemonic role in South America.
</P>
<P>
In the contemporary world, Cardoso said, it would be very
difficult for a country, even the United States, to have the
conditions necessary to impose its interests over those of others.
</P>
<P>
He said that the goal of Brazil is to share solutions with its
neighbors and to have in this way a presence in the area of
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Brazil can solve its internal problems such as poverty by
herself, he said. "Maybe it will assert some kinds of leadership
on the continent,' he said, implying that it doesn't mean seeking
a hegemonic role in South America.
</P>
<P>
Brazil should make more contributions to its neighboring
countries to help them resolve their internal issues. All this is
intended to promote mutual understanding as it did during its
mediation of peace talks between Peru and Ecuador, and the
disputes between Chile and Bolivia, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
