<HEADLINE> Air Canada, Pilots Sign Tentative Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Air Canada has signed an
agreement with its 2,200 pilots to end the lingering threat of
strike originally planned for the first day of the month.
</P>
<P>
According to an announcement released late Friday by the
country's national carrier, the airline and its pilots association
signed a memorandum of settlement on a new four-year contract,
which ensures wage increases of up to 13 percent and more job
security for the union's 2,200 members.
</P>
<P>
The association has informed both Air Canada and federal Labor
Minister Claudette Bradshaw of its decision not to issue a strike
notice.
</P>
<P>
Federal mediator Bruce Outhouse was credited for the deal,
which was based on the mediator's recommendation of a four-year
contract until April 2004.
</P>
<P>
The pilots, who are trying to narrow the wage gap with their
American counterparts, will vote on the tentative settlement in
the next few weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
