<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Olympic Shooters Aim to Repeat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Italy's shooting team is going to
the Sydney Olympics with the aim of repeating the dead-eyed form
that has made them the most feared combine around, leading the
field in the sport.
</P>
<P>
Australia could not be more auspicious turf for the Italians,
who won the first of their six gold medals in Melbourne in 1956,
with Galliano Rossini.
</P>
<P>
Since then they have accrued a total of sixteen titles
including three silvers and seven bronzes - better even than the
United States,Russia and Germany, the other top shooting nations.
</P>
<P>
In Sydney, 18 gold medals will be up for grabs in the various
disciplines which include pistol, trap, air rifle, free pistol,
double trap, rapid-fire pistol, rifle prone, running game target,
three-position rifle and skeet.
</P>
<P>
Last time out, at Atlanta, Italy bagged two golds with Roberto
Di Donna in the pistol and Ennio Falco in the skeet.
</P>
<P>
Albano Pera won a silver in the double trap and Andrea Benelli
a bronze in the skeet.
</P>
<P>
Falco and Benelli are part of the team again this time, while
Pera has gone on to train the prone rifle shooters.
</P>
<P>
Italian sports shooting federation president Luciano Rossi
acknowledged that the opponents will be tough, especially the
Australians with their home advantage, who won two golds and a
bronze four years ago.
</P>
<P>
"But all eleven of our athletes are capable of getting the gold,
" he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
