<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hingis Sends Warning to Williams Sisters in U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Martina Hingis won an easy
match to advance to the fourth round of the U.S. Open today,
sending a strong warning to the Williams sisters that she's ready
to take them on.
</P>
<P>
Hingis, who failed to win any major title since the 1999
Australian Open, defeated her Italian opponent Tathiana Garbin 6-1
and 6-0 within 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
"It will be great, definitely, to win a Grand Slam right here.
This is my chance," said the top-seeded Hingis.
</P>
<P>
Hopefully, Hingis will play Venus Williams in the semifinals,
with the winner perhaps competing against defending champion
Serena Williams in the
final.
</P>
<P>
"I watch her when she plays" Hingis said of Venus Williams, who
beat her in the Wimbledon quarterfinals en route to the title in
July. "I just have to play mine, not get too intimidated, do
whatever I've been doing so far."
</P>
<P>
Hingis will next face No. 11 Sandrine Testud who sailed over
Kristie Boogert 6-0 and 6-1, and she has won all 11 of their match,
including five this year.
</P>
<P>
In other actions of the day, sixth-seeded Monica Seles squeaked
through to the fourth round with a 6-3, 4-6, 6-4 struggle against
Chanda Rubin. After splitting the first two sets, both had
trouble holding serve and traded breaks in the fifth and sixth
games.
</P>
<P>
Next up for Seles is No. 15 Jennifer Capriati, a 6-2, 6-3
victor over Adriana Gersi. Seles has won both encounters at the U.
S. Open.
</P>
<P>
No. 8 Nathalie Tauziat downed Janet Lee 6-3, 6-2, and No. 9
Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario bested Allison Bradshaw 7-6 (7-2), 6-0.
</P>
<P>
In the men's second rounders of the day, no upsets were
produced on Friday as unseeded Todd Martin, runnerup to Andre
Agassi last year, beat Michael Chang 6-4, 6-2, 6-4, No. 3 Magnus
Norman beat Cyril Saulnier 6-3, 6-4, 6-3, No. 8 Alex Corretja beat
Marc Rosset 6-3, 7-6 (7-4), 6-3, No. 14 Nicolas Kiefer defeated
Jonas Bjorkman 6-1, 6-4, 6-3 and Sjeng Schalken stopped Adrian
Voinea 6-2, 6-3, 6-1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
