<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian President Reaffirms Creation of Free Trade Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso Friday reaffirmed the creation of a free trade
area between the Southern Common Market (Mercosur) and the
Community of Andean Nations (CAN) by January of 2002.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso made the remarks during a summit meeting of South
American countries.
</P>
<P>
The 12 presidents, who participated in the two-day summit that
ended Friday, signed the "Brasilia Communique" pledging to create
free trade between South America's two main trade blocs as soon as
possible, bringing together 340 million people in an area with a
combined economic output of 1.3 trillion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"We expect that by that time it will be possible to reduce the
differences between the countries," said Cardoso, explaining that
the integration of the South American nations was one of the
topics most discussed during the summit.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is necessary to find practical ways between the
member countries for the physical integration, and even the energy
and telecommunications integration.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso said that the Interamerican Development Bank (IDB) and
the Andean Development Corporation (CAF) are scheduling a meeting
of ministers in Montevideo, where some integration projects of the
continent will be defined. 
</P>
</TEXT>
