<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Stops Importing Cattle From Uruguay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Mexico ceased from Thursday
importing cattle on the hoof from Uruguay because of the sanitary
crisis in the region, the authorities said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Uruguay, in a bid to revert the Mexican decision, has asked
Mexico to send a team to Uruguay for an on-the-spot assessment,
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Uruguayan exports of cattle to Argentina
and of sheep to the Brazilian market have also been interrupted
due to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Foot and mouth disease outbreaks were detected in Argentina in
the first few days of August, and later in the south of Brazil and
in Bolivia. Argentina sacrificed some 3,000 heads of cattle and
suspended meat exports to the United States, Canada, Mexico and
Chile. Brazil also killed some 400 heads of cattle, pigs and sheep.
</P>
<P>
No cases of the disease have been detected so far in Uruguay,
which has closed borders with Argentina and Brazil to prevent the
contagion of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Southern Common Market (Mercosur) experts met last weekend in
Montevideo to analyze the situation and declared a sanitary alert
in the region.
</P>
<P>
The meeting decided to intensify border controls and to
restrict cattle and meat imports within the bloc. It also agreed
to send technicians to the zones, where the disease has been
detected, to find solutions to the problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
