<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Congress to Raise Minimum Wage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
on Saturday urged Congress to raise the minimum wage by one dollar
an hour to 6.15 dollars an hour.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, in his weekly radio address, said that his proposal to
raise the minimum wage has been the victim of every legislative
maneuver in the congressional handbook.
</P>
<P>
He urged Republican leaders in Congress to stop playing
legislative games and make the issue its first business when
Congress resumes after summer recess.
</P>
<P>
"Month after month, even with bipartisan support in Congress,
the Republican leadership has sat on our proposal to raise the
minimum wage," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"When they come back to Washington next week, I urge them to
send me a minimum wage bill as a first order of business," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton first proposed to raised the minimum wage by a dollar
in his State of the Union address in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
He said that his proposal means an increase of 2,000 dollars a
year for a full-time worker, enough for a family of four to buy
groceries for seven months or pay the rent check for five.
</P>
</TEXT>
