<HEADLINE> Seven Colombian Airmen Killed in Air Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Seven members of the Colombian
armed forces died Saturday when a U.S.-made Colombian warplane
crashed amid heavy fighting between leftist rebels and government
force.
</P>
<P>
A military communique said that the plane, an AC-47, crashed
early Saturday morning against a mountain over 3,000 meters above
sea level when it was taking part in the fight against the members
of the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Three officers and four technicians were aboard the plane.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft, called "phantom plane," equipped with radar for
night operation, was taking part in a support mission for the
battalions that protect a base of army communications antennas,
the National Institute of Radio and Television.
</P>
<P>
The fighting was the bloodiest since U.S. President Bill
Clinton visited Colombia on Wednesday to support President Andres
Pastrana's fight against drug traffickers and leftist rebels.
</P>
<P>
The plane, used extensively by U.S. forces during the Vietnam
War, had been providing fire support for the ground troops.
</P>
<P>
Under a new 1.3 billion-dollar aid package, Washington is
sending 60 combat helicopters to the government security forces
and elite U.S. troops are training Colombian anti-narcotics army
troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
